<TEXT>
folks in and around vattman dont even 
consider eating thanksgiving dinner at home or going off to visit 
relatives for most of this century its been a day when they all 
sit down together 
the people here in this community this is their home for that 
day said the rev sean noone irishborn pastor of the small 
roman catholic church that rises out of vattmans plowed fields 
thanksgiving has been the high point of the year in the sparsely 
populated farming area since 1913 when the annual feast began in a 
grove of mesquite trees it was canceled only in 1943 due to food 
and fuel rationing in world war ii 
and 1943 is the only time that idella strubhart 71 has ever 
eaten thanksgiving dinner at home she grew up in riviera an 
unincorporated town of 500 or so eight miles west of vattman in 
southern texas southwest of corpus christi 
she said a daughter in san antonio invited her for thaksgiving 
this year and i told her i just couldnt do it everybody has a 
job to do here 
mrs strubhart was supposed to work in the kitchen while her 
husband fritz 78 helped run the bingo game they met at the 1932 
thanksgiving dance 
what began as a small gathering has evolved into a major 
production at the parish hall of our lady of consolation church 
about the only structure that identifies vattman as a community in 
southern kleberg county the handbook of texas describes vattman as 
more a community center for nearby farming families than a 
town 
the allday party merely begins with the dinner bingo target 
shooting ring toss and other games keep the picnic going until the 
dance starts at 8 pm 
this year the parish of about 60 families expects to feed 1500 
people at its thanksgiving day picnic some former residents travel 
hundreds of miles old friends and strangers also show up 
farm and residential development began in 1908 on land the king 
ranch sold after the railroad came through predominantly german 
settlers came to farm the land now nearly all of the residents of 
northern european descent seem to be related either by blood or 
marriage 
they and their hispanic neighbors keep a slow rural pace and a 
sense of community hard to find in modern urban america weddings 
and high school football provide about the only source of public 
entertainment the rest of the year 
we grew up in sort of a naive setting here said 62yearold 
native teddy marie wallace one of this years picnic organizers 
residents donate much time and effort she said because they 
know they have something worth preserving 
i think were kind of sinfully proud of our accomplishment 
she said im sorry but we are we do a good job 
the thanksgiving dinner priced at 7 for adults and 4 for 
children also is the churchs only fundraising event the picnic 
attracts members of other denominations as well as people who 
otherwise never set foot in a church 
this years plans called for parishioners to cook 56 turkeys at 
home and take them to the church on thanksgiving day 
others prepared vegetables and desserts loretta yaklin the 
mashed potato maven remembers how the nowdefunct vattman 
parochial school she attended used to put the students to work 
preparing the parish hall the week of thanksgiving 
the pastor said picnic organizers will meet about a week after 
thanksgiving and start planning for next year 
if we ever quit it there would be a lot of people lost 
mrs yaklin said what would we do 
</TEXT>
