<TEXT>
the surprise finding earlier this year that a 76 
heart attack drug is just as good as one costing 29 times more has 
been called into question by new research released today 
the latest report bolsters the widespread skepticism among us 
physicians that greeted the release of a major italian study 
finding that the two clotdissolving medicines are equally 
effective 
both drugs are intended to break up clots that plug that hearts 
arteries during heart attacks if these clots are removed within 
four hours or so victims may escape permanent damage to their 
hearts 
the chief rivals for this lucrative market are tpa which costs 
2200 per treatment and streptokinase which costs 76 early 
us studies suggested that tpa worked better and the medicine 
quickly gained about twothirds of the us market share 
the real issue around the world is whether streptokinase is 
comparable to tpa said dr judith hsia principal author of the 
latest report its much cheaper and many countries including 
the united states would prefer to give it if it is just as good 
some thought that issue was settled last march when an italian 
study of 12490 men found that the two drugs appear equally 
effective and safe for use in routine conditions of care it 
found that about 23 percent of patients died or suffered serious 
heart damage no matter which medicine they received 
however that study made little use of a blood thinner called 
heparin which is routinely given with tpa by us doctors the new 
study shows that heparin is essential for tpa to work properly 
the latest study called the heparinaspirin reperfusion trial 
or hart was directd by dr allan m ross of george washington 
university and published in todays new england journal of 
medicine 
if you use tpa in a fashion that doesnt allow those opened 
arteries to stay open then the gain will presumably be lost 
thats the implication of hart said ross 
dr lawrence cohen of yale university agreed that the latest 
work casts doubt on the italian teams conclusion 
i think there is a distinct possibility that the survival rate 
might have been better in the tpa group had adjuvant therapy 
heparin been given in an optimal fashion cohen said 
a new study called gusto for global utilization of 
streptokinase and tpa recently began on 33000 people to settle 
whether tpa and heparin together save more lives than 
streptokinase 
answers to these questions are important financially as well as 
medically since the market for clotdissolving drugs is huge an 
estimated 15 million americans suffer heart attacks each year 
tpa is a genetically engineered human protein that is made by 
genentech streptokinase produced from bacteria is made by 
hoechst ag of germany a new entrant in the field is the 
genetically engineered eminase which is made by smithkline beecham 
and costs 1700 
tpa acts quickly in the blood stream to break up clots but the 
medicine almost immediately disappears when it is withdrawn 
streptokinase works more slowly but continues to linger in the body 
for hours after the treatment 
in the latest study researchers randomly assigned 205 heart 
attack victims to receive tpa either with or without heparin 
eighteen hours later the onceclogged arteries were flowing freely 
in 82 percent of those who got heparin and in 52 percent of those 
who did not this suggests that without heparin new clots 
frequently formed again in their arteries 
