<TEXT>
emperor akihito today began the most controversial 
ceremony in his accession to the chrysanthemum throne a communion 
with the mythical sun goddess from whom legend says the imperial 
line descended 
the shinto rite has been performed by most of japans monarchs 
since at least the seventh century and in the past was believed to 
give monarchs their status as living gods 
but protests were held across the country against the 
statefunded rite which has been criticized by many japanese as 
violating the constitutions separation of church and state 
hundreds of scholars in the north and labor unionists in the 
west held peaceful demontrations while hundreds of christians 
nationwide fasted 
about 30000 police were assigned to security in tokyo alone 
because of the threat of violence by ultraleftist radicals who 
want to abolish the monarchy 
as the ceremony began this evening radicals fired six metal 
projectiles from homemade mortarlike launchers at an imperial 
villa in kyoto western japan police said 
radicals were believed responsible for a fire that destroyed a 
shinto shrine in southern japan today police said on wednesday 
antimonarchy radicals shoveled human waste from a truck near the 
imperial palace 
akihito 56 is the first japanese emperor to be enthroned not 
as a godking but as a symbol of his peoples sovereignty but that 
has not diminished the pomp and ceremony of his multimilliondollar 
coronation 
prime minister toshiki kaifu dressed in a swallowtailed coat 
arrived at the palace this evening to attend the communion one of 
the final events surrounding the enthronement nearly 900 japanese 
dignitaries were expected to attend 
unlike akihitos formal state enthronement ceremony nov 12 that 
was viewed by foreign dignitaries representing 158 countries no 
foreigners were invited to the communion which is to end before 
dawn friday 
during the rite called the daijosai or great food offering 
ritual akihito offers rice wine and other foods from around the 
country to the sun goddess amaterasu from whom legend says the 
imperial line descended 
only two female attendants clad in white and red kimono and 
with their hair tied in pony tails nearly 6 feet long witness the 
daijosai the ceremony is held in the torchlit inner sanctuary of 
a specially built hall on the palace grounds the rite is performed 
only once by each emperor 
akihito wearing his most holy white silk robes for the rite and 
surrounded by court chamberlains slowly proceeded to the 
sanctuary led by two attendants lighting the way with torches 
other attendants carried a large parasol over akihitos head or 
unrolled a rush mat before him yet another rolled up the mat 
behind the emperor after each deliberate step 
inside the sanctuary out of view of the 733 japanese guests 
seated in large tents nearby the offerings were to be made to an 
altar placed beside a stylized bed from which the goddess is 
summoned 
scholars before world war ii theorized that at one time the 
ceremony might have involved the emperor symbolically having sex 
with the sun goddess representing a union with the divine palace 
officials however deny that theory and said the emperor would not 
touch the bed 
after the first communion this evening the ceremony was to be 
repeated after midnight in an identical hall located just yards 
away from the first one haunting court music was to be played 
throughout 
akihito like his father the late emperor hirohito performs 
dozens of religious ceremonies at the palace each year carrying on 
the priestking role that has been handed down from ancient times 
that role however has periodically come under fire since the 
end of world war ii and opposition political parties christian 
organizations and other groups claim the government is violation 
the constitutional separation of church and state by spending an 
estimated 17 million on the coronation rites 
hirohito who died in january 1989 at age 87 renounced the 
concept of imperial divinity on new years day 1946 at the urging 
of the usled occupation forces the countrys postwar 
constitution specifies that the emperor is a national symbol and 
not a godking as tradition had had it 
critics say repeating the shinto rites for akihitos 
enthronement could encourage a return to the feverish 
emperorworship that helped lead the nation into war 
