<TEXT>
a fouryear boom that brought a new era of 
affluence to japan appears to be subsiding as a labor shortage 
higher interest rates and the persian gulf crisis take their toll 
on the economy 
demand for domestic goods and strong corporate investment will 
insulate the economy from the worst of the us economic downturn 
and ensure that land prices fall gradually rather than plummet 
said russell jones an economist at ubs phillips and drew 
international ltd 
but growing corporate bankruptcies and lackluster midyear 
corporate profits are signs that the economy is shifting into lower 
gear after four years of annual growth of 5 percent or more 
analysts say 
the economys beginning to slow but its a slow slowdown the 
deceleration is not that pronounced its not a collapse jones 
said 
most economists cite higher interest rates introduced to cool 
inflation as a key constraint especially for smaller firms that 
borrow for investment 
the bank of japan has raised the official rate it charges 
commercial banks five times since may 1989 from 25 percent to 6 
percent that has ended the source of cheap capital that helped 
fuel the boom that began in december 1986 
partly because of higher interest rates corporate bankruptcies 
in japan increased in october for the first time in 70 months 
climbing 97 percent from the year before to 645 cases teikoku 
data bank reported 
hardest hit were real estate firms weakened by flattening land 
prices and small and mediumsize manufacturers suffering from a 
severe labor shortage the private credit research agency said 
at the same time companies found their financial cushions of 
stock assets flattened by lower share prices 
the nikkei stock average the tokyo markets key indicator has 
dropped more than 40 percent this year the return on financial 
assets has plummeted and cheap equity financing has become 
difficult said masahide tsuru of the long term credit banks 
economics division 
the bankruptcies indicate the impact of the labor shortage and 
interest rates at the operating level at the recurring level 
declines in the equity and bond markets are compounding 
everything said peter morgan chief economist at barclays de 
zoete wedd securities japan 
a survey by wako research institute of economics showed that 
profits of major corporations for the sixmonth period ending in 
september climbed only 003 percent from the same period in 1989 
during the previous six months profits climbed 144 percent from a 
year earlier 
the survey excluded banks and securities firms whose profits 
have fallen sharply with the nikkeis plunge 
manufacturers meanwhile are facing lower demand from importers 
in the united states which is undergoing a more pronounced 
downturn japanese semiconductor manufacturers have already 
announced they will slash computer chip output because of lower 
demand from us importers 
growth in consumer spending which accounts for about 60 percent 
of gross national product has begun to slow partly because of the 
bearish financial markets 
higher interest rates also have made credit purchases of major 
items such as cars and homes much more costly said johsen 
takahashi director of the private thinktank mitsubishi research 
institute 
consumption which grew steadily by 2 percent to 3 percent until 
may began to slow in july it rose only 06 percent in september 
from a year earlier marking the slowest growth this year the 
management and coordination agency said in a report released 
wednesday 
not all the economic news is bad for japan though lower us 
interest rates have tended to weaken the dollar making the yen 
relatively stronger noted barclays de zoete wedds peter morgan 
that means japanese products are more expensive abroad but 
imports of fuel and other goods are cheaper thats become 
increasingly important with surging oil prices caused by the middle 
east crisis 
barring a major cut in oil supplies economists expect japans 
economy to continue chugging along although at a slower pace most 
expect economic growth to remain at a robust 5 percent to 6 percent 
in 1990 and to level off over the next several years to around 4 
percent 
this isnt going to be a recession there wont be a huge fall 
in the standard of living said lawrence s prager chief analyst 
and strategist at nikko securites co its just a slowdown 
