<TEXT>
the backers of two proposed cable television 
channels devoted to covering the legal system have decided to 
cooperate on a single courtroom network avoiding what could have 
been a costly competition 
the courtroom television network is expected to be launched next 
summer 
time warner inc which hoped to launch its own courtroom 
network next year and national broadcasting co and the 
programming division of cablevision systems corp which were 
developing a similar service said wednesday they agreed to form a 
partnership to create a channel devoted exclusively to coverage of 
the courts and legal issues 
terms were not disclosed the deal is subject to approval by 
their respective boards 
the plan calls for time warner to manage the new service through 
its affiliate american lawyer media lp which publishes 11 legal 
titles including the monthly american lawyer magazine american 
lawyer president and chief executive steven brill will be chief 
executive of the joint cable venture 
the courtroom television network will provide continuous live 
and taped coverage of trials legal reports and commentary from 
legal experts 
its backers say there is a big audience for television that 
focuses on legal issues 
but planners of the competing services found many cable tv 
systems simply didnt have extra channel space for two legal 
networks and were slow in picking between them a tight capital 
market meanwhile has made it more difficult for operators to 
raise money for expansion of channel capacity 
the operators are as a result prudent and cautious in adding 
new services said sharon patrick president of cablevisions 
rainbow programming holdings inc but we feel that combining the 
distribution the capital and the talent of the two of them creates 
the strongest new service in cable 
time warner owns cable operations with an estimated 64 million 
household subscribers while cablevision systems has about 16 
million subscribers 
discussions are underway with other cable systems about taking 
the courtroom channel 
cablevision systems had originally planned to have its courtroom 
cable network called in court in operation this fall it hired 
arthur miller the harvard law professor as its chief legal 
analyst and a staff of about 15 to 20 other people ms patrick 
said 
time warner has never disclosed a proposed launch date for its 
courtroom service which was tentatively called the american 
courtroom network 
it hired fred graham formerly the supreme court reporter for 
the new york times and cbs news as its chief anchor 
graham will take that role on the proposed network and miller 
floyd abrams f lee bailey david boies robert bork arthur liman 
and barry slotnick will serves as commentators the network will 
also draw on work from american lawyers more than 200 legal 
journalists 
larry gerbrandt who follows the cable industry for paul kagan 
associates in carmel calif said the combination of the two 
proposed legal channels makes it more likely that a courtroom 
channel will succeed 
this is not an environment where either time warner or 
cablevision wants to sustain longterm losses combined this 
network has a chance to launch much faster be larger and be more 
profitable more quickly he said 
he noted that two cable comedy channels for instance were 
launched in the past year but neither has approached the 25 million 
subscribers he says are needed to attract advertisers and generate 
sufficient licensing fees to cover overhead costs about 54 million 
us households get cable tv 
time warners comedy channel launched in november 1989 is on 
systems with 75 million subscribers while viacom incs ha 
channel has 65 million 
talks about merging those services broke off earlier this year 
the comedy wars have been plenty expensive gerbrandt said 
he agreed there may be an appetite for a legal channel 
its americas ultimate ongoing theater he said 
