<TEXT>
economic factors contributed to prime minister 
margaret thatchers downfall though reforming the economy was one 
of the hallmarks of more than 11 years of thatcherism 
during her tenure at 10 downing st mrs thatcher relentlessly 
promoted capitalism to defeat socialism in britain 
she took over from the previous labor government a troubled 
economy that was suffering from 17 percent interest rates and moved 
deep into recession while inflation climbed to 18 percent 
mrs thatcher tamed militant labor unions reformed taxes and 
cut many inefficiencies out of british industry her efforts helped 
produce an eightyear economic boom the longest in britain since 
world war ii during which interest rates fell to 75 percent 
inflation got down to 33 percent and unemployment went from 113 
percent to 55 percent 
but her hostility toward european economic and monetary union 
her unpopular percapita community charge or polltax and the 
downturn in the economy made her vulnerable to the attack on her 
leadership of the conservative party 
to guard british sovereignty she said she wouldnt abolish the 
pound to make way for a single european currency or relinquish 
monetary control to a european central bank but other 
conservatives and many britons worried about being left behind in 
the european economic revolution 
the poll tax which went into effect earlier this year was 
unpopular enough to also divide her party and spark riots 
the tax was intended to make local government authorities 
accountable for their spending but it condemned for having no 
relationship to the taxpayers ability to pay 
the economic downturn has been accompanied by 14 percent 
interest rates 109 percent inflation and huge trade deficits 
unemployment at 6 percent has been climbing 
the government had pushed interest rates higher leaving them at 
15 percent for a year to fight the resurgent inflation by cooling 
demand 
demand had overheated because of loose monetary policy designed 
to improve the conservatives electoral prospects in 1987 and to 
avoid a recession following the stock market crash in october of 
that year 
high interest rates have hurt industry and profits and britain 
is suffering record business failures the rates also have squeezed 
britains new homeowners who generally hold adjustable rate 
mortgages 
the persistent bear market on the stock exchange meanwhile has 
hurt some 9 million britons who have become new shareholders 
asked about mrs thatchers accomplishments economist kevin 
darlington of the london investment firm ubs phillips and drew 
said the true test will be whether the underlying economy is 
strong enough to cope with the current recession 
mrs thatcher said in the house of commons thursday that her 
government had improved the standard of living in britain 
this past week she said that one of her main achievements was 
creating a culture of enterprise that oversaw the restructuring of 
britains overmanned inefficient industry into a leaner more 
competitive one 
the major accomplishment i think must be the enormous surge 
in british productivity the change in management attitudes she 
got rid of slack management and the weakening of union power 
said john barnes who teaches government at the london school of 
economics 
at least part of the 11 12 years in office she succeeded in 
beating inflation barnes said the generation of small business 
was also a thatcher accomplishment he said 
through largescale privatization that has been copied around 
the world mrs thatcher deregulated utilities turned nationalized 
companies such as british airways into worldclass competitors and 
more than tripled british share ownership 
britains financial markets also were deregulated under the 
socalled big bang which opened securities trading to banks and 
foreign traders in 1986 
she tamed britains militant unions with legislation that 
required them to ballot workers before they go on strike and union 
membership has declined substantially to 84 million from 12 
million in 1979 
mrs thatcher also promoted home ownership by selling public 
housing to its tenants 
she cut and simplified taxes over the years she brought the 
basic income tax rate to 25 percent from 33 percent and nearly 
halved the top rate to 40 percent from 83 percent 
she put a tight grip on public spending and tried to break a 
british dependence on welfare thus she turned the budget deficits 
into the surpluses 
the prime minister also encouraged entrepreneurship trying to 
turn britain from a classdivided society into a meritocracy some 
400000 new businesses have been created since 1979 she said 
</TEXT>
