<TEXT>
prime minister margaret thatchers resignation 
thursday was bittersweet news for britains business community and 
financial markets 
they were sorry to see mrs thatcher go because her staunch 
freemarket policies have transformed british industry during her 
11 years in power 
but they were relieved that she stepped aside to improve the 
capitalist conservative partys chances of defeating the socialist 
laborites in the next election which must be called by mid1992 
they were dismayed that more than one new leadership contender 
stepped forward raising doubts about the conservative election 
changes and fueling fears that the leadership battle would be 
prolonged 
some traders were cheered that chancellor of the exchequer john 
major was one of two new candidates believing the treasurys top 
official could help turn britains ailing economy turn around 
foreign secretary douglas hurd also said he would challenge 
michael hesletine the former defense minister who won enough votes 
last tuesday to force a second ballot next tuesday and prompt mrs 
thatcher to step down 
traders said mrs thatchers announcement caught the financial 
community like most everyone else offguard especially after her 
determined statement wednesday that she would fight on 
but kevin darlington a british economist with the london 
investment firm ubs phillips and drew said there was not the 
kind of fallout in the stock market or sterling that might have 
been expected because the worst already has been anticipated 
the pound and share prices soared when news of her resignation 
broke in the morning then fell back after hurd and major emerged 
before the noon deadline for nominations 
the market is going mad in relief said peter furlong 
senior british equities dealer at daiwa securities 
one buoyant factor during the day was widespread speculation 
that the conservative government would launch the new postthatcher 
regime with a quick halfpoint cut in britains 14 percent 
interest rates 
the strong pound would allow an interest rate cut without 
